16	\n\t\t\n\t\t<h1>How we designed Sigfig's Mobile ui and grew users 500%&nbsp;</h1>\n\t\n\t	\n\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\t\n\t\t<p>Over the past three months, I've been a StartUp Academy Fellow for Bain Capital Ventures, working at their portfolio company SigFig. Here are a few tips I picked up on building an easy-to-user mobile UI.</p><p>When conceptualizing your mobile app’s user interface, there are a few things that you should keep in mind. Some of the basic things such as clarity of interface, consistency from one view to the next, and making sure that tapping on any button or UI element provides feedback to the user are fairly straightforward and are generally, though not universally, followed by most app designers.</p><p><br></p><p><img alt="Id 1 name bain capital ventures articleid 16" src="http://localhost:3000/system/investors/snapshots/000/000/001/original/id-1-name-bain-capital-ventures-articleid-16.png"><br></p><p><b><i>1 – Ideal button size</i></b></p><p>This is a fairly obvious issue.</p><p>Button sizes are generally limited by the size of our fingers, and so if they are too small, users will be unable to touch them accurately. &nbsp;Button widths below 1cm are harder (and slower) to touch. &nbsp;Aside from the minimum size, there are some benefits to non-uniform button sizes (they give an indication to novice users as to which button is more important).</p><p><i>+more</i></p><p><br></p><p>- Interested? SigFig is looking for UI/UX interns. Click <a href="/">here</a> for more information.&nbsp;</p><p><i>Click&nbsp;<a href="/">here</a> to learn more about the StartUp Academy</i></p><!-- end-of-image-div -->\n\t\n\t\n\t\n\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t</div><!-- end-of-image-div -->\n\t\n\t\n\t\n\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t</div><!-- end-of-image-div -->\n\t\n\t\n\t\n\n\t\t<div>\n\t\t</div><!-- end-of-image-div -->\n\t	\N	\N	\N	1	\N	\N
